<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-165-068 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 531 262</DOCID><JOURNAL>Macworld  May 1991 v8 n5 p23(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Laptop on my mind: why we're still waiting on Apple. (Commentary)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Borrell, Jerry.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>In 1989, Japan's Sony Corp offered Apple Computer Inc a portablecomputer, small enough to be held in the palm of a hand, based onthe Motorola 68000 processor.andP;  The computer also included a QWERTYkeyboard, a 125Mbyte optical drive, a small LCD display, functionkeys, a 'virtual mouse' and a stereo headphone port for users tolisten to sound or music.andP;  Sony wanted to offer Apple exclusiverights to market the product in return for Apple providing itsm Macintosh Operating System for the machine.andP;  Apple refused, sayingit was already developing such a machine.andP;  Apple never developedsuch a product and Sony's Data Discman is currently selling wellin Japan.andP;  It is unfortunate that Apple turned the Data Discmandown since the machine, coupled with the Macintosh OperatingSystem could have been a major product.andP;  The ideal unit, however,would be a notebook with a color display, a 125Mbyte optical driveand a virtual mouse.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (Product development)Sony Corp. (Product development).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Product:   Sony Data Discman (Portable computer) (Product development).andO;Topic:     Portable computersCritiqueProduct DevelopmentJapanMarketing StrategyConsumer electronicsHand-Held Computers.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>